00:00:05.910 --> 00:00:07.650
Student: Yes
Prof: Are you from Seoul?

00:00:07.650 --> 00:00:08.650
Student:  Yeah.
 

00:00:08.650 --> 00:00:11.390
Prof: You may know about
this, okay.

00:00:11.390 --> 00:00:19.780
There's a--do you know about
the oldest tree in Seoul?

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:22.210
Student: No.
 

00:00:22.210 --> 00:00:24.930
Prof: This is the oldest
tree in Seoul.

00:00:24.930 --> 00:00:28.395
It's a Gingko tree,
and it's supposed to be 840

00:00:28.395 --> 00:00:32.915
years old, that's a really old
tree and it's venerated by the

00:00:32.915 --> 00:00:33.970
residents.
 

00:00:33.970 --> 00:00:37.602
It's kind of a holy sacred tree
and they bring fruit,

00:00:37.602 --> 00:00:40.885
they bring other offerings once
a year and pray,

00:00:40.885 --> 00:00:43.750
among other things,
for their safety.

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:48.857
Its real advantage is that it
helps pregnant women to have a

00:00:48.857 --> 00:00:53.100
boy child and so this is a very
important tree.

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:55.400
Do you know about this tree?
 

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:56.280
Student:  No.
 

00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:57.160
Prof: No.
 

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:00.514
Student:  But I've heard
about Gingko trees and how they

00:01:00.514 --> 00:01:02.570
have to do with fertility and
stuff.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:04.962
Prof: Yes,
okay Ginkgo is one of the few

00:01:04.962 --> 00:01:07.409
kinds of trees that have male
and female sex.

00:01:07.409 --> 00:01:11.049
Most trees are hermaphrodite,
have both male and female sex.

00:01:11.049 --> 00:01:14.094
Anyway, it turns out they ran
into a problem with this tree

00:01:14.094 --> 00:01:17.351
because two apartment buildings
were interfering with the trees

00:01:17.351 --> 00:01:19.400
roots as the tree spread its
roots.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:23.691
What happens--so the district
government spent $4.3 million

00:01:23.691 --> 00:01:27.170
dollars to take down the
apartment buildings.

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:31.352
So it just goes to show you the
importance and the political

00:01:31.352 --> 00:01:34.402
acceptability,
the cultural acceptability of

00:01:34.402 --> 00:01:35.750
son preference.
 

00:01:35.750 --> 00:01:39.599
It's a very,
very big factor in the world.

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:42.878
The sex ratio,
is a very important biological

00:01:42.878 --> 00:01:47.200
factor, if we have time at the
end I'll tell you a good bit

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:48.170
about it.
 

00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:53.593
Just to show you that it's very
well controlled biologically,

00:01:53.593 --> 00:01:58.745
this is one of several theories
about how the sex ratio in

00:01:58.745 --> 00:02:01.730
humans gets to be what it is.
 

00:02:01.730 --> 00:02:03.670
The sperms are 50/50.
 

00:02:03.670 --> 00:02:09.235
There's 100 male sperms to 100
female sperms and that's because

00:02:09.235 --> 00:02:14.532
the sex is determined by the
father and the father has one X

00:02:14.532 --> 00:02:17.771
and one Y,
and when they split to go into

00:02:17.771 --> 00:02:20.483
separate sperms one gets an X,
one gets a Y,

00:02:20.483 --> 00:02:21.430
that's even.
 

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:24.186
By the second month of
gestation, so this is still in

00:02:24.186 --> 00:02:27.857
the mother's womb,
apparently a huge fraction of

00:02:27.857 --> 00:02:32.090
about one-third of the male
fetuses have died,

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:39.008
leaving--I'm sorry the female
fetuses have died because now

00:02:39.008 --> 00:02:41.990
it's a high male ratio.
 

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:46.971
Then as time goes on the male
fetuses start to die and when

00:02:46.971 --> 00:02:52.467
you end up, you get 106 at birth
all over the world unless people

00:02:52.467 --> 00:02:54.530
are messing with it.
 

00:02:54.530 --> 00:03:00.628
There's about 106 male births
to every 100 female births.

00:03:00.628 --> 00:03:03.341
This is a very,
very fixed number,

00:03:03.341 --> 00:03:06.955
so for instance,
in the United States in 1969

00:03:06.955 --> 00:03:10.900
there were 105.3 males born per
100 females;

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:18.860
1995 30 something years later
104.9, so difference of .4.

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:24.306
That number really does not
vary except basically between

00:03:24.306 --> 00:03:25.669
105 and 106.
 

00:03:25.669 --> 00:03:31.979
It's a very, very stable number.
 

00:03:31.979 --> 00:03:37.098
Given that, you can look at
some parts of the world and see

00:03:37.098 --> 00:03:39.038
something like this.
 

00:03:39.038 --> 00:03:44.490
This is again the sex ratio and
you can look over time,

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:51.681
1972 to 1992 a 20 year span and
here is Japan where they started

00:03:51.681 --> 00:03:55.223
a little bit of X--
here's the numbers you should

00:03:55.223 --> 00:03:57.348
expect,
somewhere in this range.

00:03:57.348 --> 00:04:02.217
They have somewhat of an excess
of boys but very minor and than

00:04:02.217 --> 00:04:07.241
during this period of time Japan
came down to almost exactly that

00:04:07.241 --> 00:04:08.419
106 number.
 

00:04:08.419 --> 00:04:13.258
Look at what's going on in
China, up to 113 or so,

00:04:13.258 --> 00:04:19.086
which means basically seven out
of every 100 girls are being

00:04:19.086 --> 00:04:21.259
done away with 7%.
 

00:04:21.259 --> 00:04:26.449
That's not anywhere near the
worst case.

00:04:26.449 --> 00:04:31.629
What do you think is the cause
of this?

00:04:31.629 --> 00:04:33.589
Student:  Mitochondrial
DNA.

00:04:33.589 --> 00:04:34.779
Prof: Mitochondrial DNA?
 

00:04:34.779 --> 00:04:38.449
Student: 
&gt;

00:04:38.449 --> 00:04:42.160
mitochondrial DNA can choose to
eliminate male fetuses.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:44.750
Prof: So you think it's
a very long term evolutionary--

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:48.300
what she's saying is she
thinks--there's stuff that--

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:55.230
the Y--the sperm--the Y
chromosome has very few genes,

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:57.889
the X chromosome has many genes.
 

00:04:57.889 --> 00:05:02.785
There looks like there's a long
evolutionary process by which

00:05:02.785 --> 00:05:06.129
genes are getting eliminated on
the Y,

00:05:06.129 --> 00:05:08.517
and eventually the Y will then
have nothing on it and

00:05:08.517 --> 00:05:09.069
disappear.
 

00:05:09.069 --> 00:05:12.314
This is much too short a time,
we're talking ten years,

00:05:12.314 --> 00:05:15.738
evolution just doesn't happen
in ten years but it's a good

00:05:15.738 --> 00:05:16.459
thought.
 

00:05:16.459 --> 00:05:18.365
Student:  Does it have
something to do with the

00:05:18.365 --> 00:05:19.839
implementation of the one child
policy;

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:24.730
people wanting sons as opposed
to daughters.

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:25.800
Prof: Very good.
 

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:30.889
This is the most usual answer:
the one child policy in China.

00:05:30.889 --> 00:05:33.464
This is China remember and the
one child policy,

00:05:33.464 --> 00:05:36.750
so people have heard of the one
child policy and I'm going to

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:38.120
give a lecture on it.
 

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:41.769
Does that sound like a good
hypothesis to you?

00:05:41.769 --> 00:05:45.000
But just saying it doesn't make
it true, so what else did--

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.360
Student:  This is at
birth.

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:47.519
Prof: This is at birth.
 

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:50.567
Student:  How could
you--even if you wanted sons I

00:05:50.567 --> 00:05:53.670
presume that the greatest way to
manage that would through

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:56.720
infanticide and you can't do
that until after birth.

00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:58.290
Prof: Very good idea.
 

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:01.180
What she says is look this is
at birth.

00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:03.278
Students:
 &gt;

00:06:03.278 --> 00:06:09.189
Prof: Good,
I'm glad all this discussion.

00:06:09.189 --> 00:06:11.139
Let's notice one other thing.
 

00:06:11.139 --> 00:06:14.377
One child policy,
when does the one child policy

00:06:14.377 --> 00:06:14.930
start?
 

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:16.769
We'll come back to these
explanations;

00:06:16.769 --> 00:06:18.290
they're all good.
 

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:21.279
Anybody know?
 

00:06:21.279 --> 00:06:24.350
Guess what, about 1979,1980.
 

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:27.709
When does this take off?
 

00:06:27.709 --> 00:06:33.492
That looks like now we've got
at least a second piece of

00:06:33.492 --> 00:06:39.591
evidence that it's--the time
sequence fits very nicely with

00:06:39.591 --> 00:06:42.220
the one child policy.
 

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:43.790
How can we check that?
 

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:46.315
We're still--we have to be very
skeptical about everything that

00:06:46.315 --> 00:06:49.129
anyone tells you;
that's the scientific attitude.

00:06:49.129 --> 00:06:51.310
Anything anybody tells you,
politics,

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:53.564
science, religion,
economics, try to sell you

00:06:53.564 --> 00:06:55.916
something,
immediate gut response is

00:06:55.916 --> 00:06:58.209
'that's nonsense prove it to
me.'

00:06:58.209 --> 00:07:01.509
I'm not convinced yet so what
else might you do?

00:07:01.509 --> 00:07:04.420
Student:  If you can
find data on abortions.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:06.574
Prof: You could find
data on abortions,

00:07:06.574 --> 00:07:06.910
good.
 

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:10.240
We'll look at that when we talk
about China.

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:12.790
We might look at other
countries that don't have the

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:13.740
one child policy.
 

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:17.569
Here's another country,
this is India,

00:07:17.569 --> 00:07:23.468
and you have--remember the
Chinese--and this is a somewhat

00:07:23.468 --> 00:07:25.850
different data set.
 

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:30.473
This is not at birth but the
total population which is less

00:07:30.473 --> 00:07:32.468
extreme,
but a comparable number for

00:07:32.468 --> 00:07:35.449
China would be here,
so India is more extreme than

00:07:35.449 --> 00:07:35.949
